# Admin app components and UI

The admin app should feel like a focused operational tool: dense enough for repeated work, polished enough to trust, and consistent across media domains. Use existing shadcn-style primitives and admin components before inventing new UI.

## UI primitive policy

- Always prefer existing shadcn-style primitives from `src/components/ui`.
- Installing new shadcn components is allowed when existing primitives are insufficient.
- Before adding a new primitive, search `src/components/ui` and nearby feature components.
- Do not create custom one-off controls when a shadcn primitive already fits.
- Use Radix/shadcn patterns for dialogs, dropdowns, popovers, selects, checkboxes, tables, tabs, sheets, accordions, tooltips, alerts, and scroll areas.
- Use `lucide-react` icons for buttons and visual affordances.
- Keep icons from lucide unless a feature has a specific reason for another icon source.

## Admin visual style

- Admin UI should be quiet, structured, and work-focused.
- Prioritize scanning, repeated actions, comparison, and predictable layout.
- Avoid public-site landing page patterns, hero marketing sections, decorative illustrations, and oversized copy.
- Do not add a broad visual redesign while implementing a feature.
- Preserve the dark-mode admin shell unless the design system is deliberately changed.
- Keep colors and gradients consistent with the existing admin app. Avoid one-off decorative palettes.
- Use cards/panels for actual grouped tools, repeated items, dialogs, dashboard summaries, and tables.
- Do not nest cards inside cards unless the inner element is a real repeated item or control surface.

## Component structure

- Keep one primary React component per component/page file.
- Split very large or hard-to-scan components into focused subcomponents.
- It is acceptable for a file to contain tiny local skeletons or private helper components when they are tightly tied to the page.
- Move repeated, meaningful subviews into separate files.
- Keep components focused on layout, wiring, and user interaction.
- Move multi-step state orchestration into hooks.
- Use config arrays plus `.map()` for repeated sibling controls when the repeated shape is stable.
- Avoid long stacks of nearly identical JSX.

## Component exports

- Use one primary React component per component file.
- Prefer default function exports for primary components:

```tsx
export default function MediaListHeader(props: MediaListHeaderProps) {
  // ...
}
```

- Use named exports for helper builders and config values when they are imported by multiple files.
- Keep file-private prop types and helper types unexported unless another file imports them.
- When grouping siblings without extra DOM, use `<Fragment>...</Fragment>` with `import { Fragment } from "react"` rather than empty fragment shorthand `<>...</>`.

## Forms and controls

- Use appropriate controls for the job:
  - select menus for finite option sets
  - checkbox/toggle controls for binary state
  - inputs for free text or numeric values
  - month picker for month selection
  - buttons only for commands
  - dialogs/sheets for modal workflows
- Validate and normalize input before sending it to services.
- Keep labels short and clear.
- Make destructive actions explicit with confirmation dialogs.
- Disable submit/action buttons while mutations are pending.
- Show loading states for long-running actions.
- Do not let text overflow buttons, badges, table cells, or dialog headers.

## Dialogs and modals

- Use shadcn dialog/alert-dialog primitives.
- Keep dialog trigger controls eager and lightweight.
- Lazy-load heavy dialog bodies when the user chooses that workflow.
- Render interaction-loaded lazy dialogs only when active.
- A `Suspense fallback={null}` is acceptable for a modal body that appears immediately after a click, but consider a small spinner if loading is noticeable.
- Closing a dialog should clean up dialog-local state when appropriate.
- Do not keep stale selected items, duplicate maps, search terms, or active detail state after closing add-media dialogs.

## Tables and lists

- Use TanStack Table for structured entity tables.
- Keep row IDs stable and based on backend IDs.
- Keep table pagination controlled by backend metadata.
- Show empty states and loading states.
- Keep bulk delete behavior explicit and confirmed.
- Media library list rows should remain optimized for scanning:
  - poster/title
  - media type
  - status/progress
  - score/review metadata
  - primary row actions
- Infinite media lists should have a sentinel and a manual "Load more" escape hatch where the current pattern does that.

## Review editor

- Keep the public API of `ReviewEditor` stable:
  - `review`
  - `setReview`
  - `mediaType`
  - `reviewId`
  - `setUploadedImages`
- The heavy markdown editor package should remain lazy-loaded internally.
- Preserve the stable 400px loading placeholder so layout does not jump while the editor chunk loads.
- Preserve paste/upload integration.
- Preserve review editor dark styling.
- Do not import `@uiw/react-md-editor` statically in route or review section files.

## Dashboard

- Dashboard widgets should stay modular:
  - KPI cards
  - library health
  - media consumption
  - taste profile
  - recent activity
  - top rated sections
- Recharts should remain isolated behind the lazy-loaded dashboard route unless the chart architecture changes.
- Dashboard query hooks should live in `src/hooks/useDashboardQueries.ts`.
- Keep dashboard loading/error states clear and compact.

## Accessibility and behavior

- Use semantic buttons for actions.
- Use links for navigation.
- Keep `aria-label` on icon-only buttons.
- Do not remove focus-visible styles.
- Dialogs should remain keyboard accessible through shadcn/Radix primitives.
- Keep images with useful alt text when the image conveys content; use empty alt only for decorative thumbnails where nearby text already labels the item.

## What not to do

- Do not create a custom UI primitive when a shadcn primitive exists.
- Do not eagerly load heavy dialog bodies.
- Do not import markdown editor or chart-heavy modules into the root bundle unless unavoidable.
- Do not hide mutation progress from the user.
- Do not use service calls directly in components instead of mutations.
- Do not add visible instructional text about how the UI works unless the workflow genuinely needs it.
